threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a classic malicious dropper/loader. Analysis of the entry point (_start) reveals that it performs several stages of self-extraction and execution. It first decrypts an internal string using a hardcoded XOR key (0xd9) to create a mutex. It then accesses its own executable file on disk, moves the file pointer to the end of the file (EOF) to read an overlay containing a dynamic XOR key and a secondary payload. The binary decrypts this payload in memory, writes it to a new file (after attempting to delete/modify attributes of a potential existing target), and executes the dropped file via CreateProcessA. Concrete behaviors include self-reading (GetModuleFileNameA/ReadFile), XOR-based obfuscation, and process injection/dropping.
